
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `file` baraye tashkhis noe file estefade mishavad. In dastoor mi-toone beghe che noee file dari (masalan, matni, tasvir, ya barname).

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `file filename`  --> 📄 Tashkhis noe file ba esm `filename`.
    🔹 `file -b filename` --> 💬 Fagat noe file ra chap mikonad, bedoon esm file.
    🔹 `file -i filename` --> ℹ️ Namayesh noe MIME file (masalan, text/plain ya image/jpeg).

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ file myfile.txt

    🔹 Tashkhis noe file `myfile.txt`.

    $ file -b myimage.jpg

    🔹 Fagat noe file `myimage.jpg` ra chap mikonad.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ file -i myfile.txt

    🔹 Agar `myfile.txt` yek file matni bashad, natije `text/plain` khahad bood.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `file` command is used to determine the file type. It can tell you what kind of file you have (e.g., text, image, or program).

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `file filename`  --> 📄 Determine the type of the file named `filename`.
    🔹 `file -b filename` --> 💬 Print only the file type, without the filename.
    🔹 `file -i filename` --> ℹ️ Display the MIME type of the file (e.g., text/plain or image/jpeg).

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ file myfile.txt

    🔹 Determine the type of the file `myfile.txt`.

    $ file -b myimage.jpg

    🔹 Print only the type of the file `myimage.jpg`.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ file -i myfile.txt

    🔹 If `myfile.txt` is a text file, the output will be `text/plain`.

